author: ErythWolf
text:
Checkpoint:
10/26/20

There's some bitter irony to this song. Recently, I took a risk on a friend, and suffice it to say, it completely backfired. He said he didn't want to be friends anymore. It still hurts. I'll always care for him, but our differences were just too much to overcome for him. I chose to not struggle and pull at what made us so close. I wanted to keep the memories and that tapestry unfrayed. He actually linked me to a cover of this song. So while I'm glad to bump into another checkpoint, I feel like this one is sorta painful, I guess. Sorta like when people lose a party member in a story. Maybe we'll meet again on better terms, but for now, I'll continue down my own path, without him. 

 There's still joy to forging my own path. Just today, I took another risk with some friends that were in a tough spot, and man am I glad that I meddled a little. They just needed a gentle push to resolve things, and I feel at peace that it worked out. It doesn't really benefit me in any way, but I care about them so much, that I couldn't bear to see another friendship fall apart. They need to work a few things out, but I have faith that they'll work through it all. 

To anybody reading this, please, if things can be worked out for the best, if you aren't toxic for each other, please keep close to those you love. As these words meant something to you, they now mean something to me, Haru. Best of luck where ever you are~

Have these troubles brought you pain, my friends?
Let your worries wash away
When the world's got you down and time can't be found to
Treat those burning wounds just remember
The table is set and your bed's always made
In the place that you once called home

author: lucky leo's thoughts
text:
It is more than calm, it has a sense of home woven into it. Not merely peaceful, but peaceful because of its familiarity with its welcoming quality. The coziness of a few intimate friends/family who you know would never do you wrong. 

Here is a particular example: You had a rough day at work and traffic was terrible but when you come home and open the door your spouse greets you with a big hug and you can smell the aroma of pumpkin pie baking in the oven, your favorite. Your wonderful children all show you their mostly good report cards and you sit down into your comfy lazyboy chair and you forget you even had a rough day the the office.

author: DÃ¤rk ClÃ¸ud
text:
Read For Good Chrono Nostalgic Vibes!!

Like everyone else's Chrono Triggered memories, mine begin in the summer time... Sitting in a darkened room wrapped up in a fleece blanket in front of my Sanyo Tube TV, with my SNES at my feet,  and snacks that eventually got sat out overnight and became stale after falling asleep to the music in the land of Zeal. Janus had revealed his true identity, Chrono had been rebirthed with a magical egg, Glenn had confided in everyone -- in US about his darkened past, and why the Masamune was so important to him. Marle had realized how deep her royal lineage truly was thanks to Ayla, and Ayla had realized how important her role was in the way the world had began to shape itself into the world it eventually became for each and every one of the characters in the game. Luca and her Father had reconciled with her regretful, and hard-to-forget past that cost her mother her life, and it was because of Luca that Robo was able to transcend past his unfortunate circumstances, and truly realize he was despite being a machine also an existent being that was more than what he was designated to be. Janus was able to reconcile his absence from Zeal, and despite the pain that Schala and he had felt were in their own ways able to find retribution for the eventual sins their superiors -- and even their own family had ultimately succumbed to as far as Lavos, or the Frozen Flame is concerned for in that matter. 

Of course there are many other characters who without their contributions that the shape of their world that it took on wouldn't have been able to sustain itself without the events that occured because of their roles they played. For example: Jasper wouldn't have needed to remove himself from the pocket of time he ultimately found himself in to have spared his own life because he was already fated to exist in that realm far before Chrono woke up late that morning of the festival which began everyone's adventure to defeat Lavos. Melchior didn't have to put himself through so much suffering or burden that his character had carried, he could have chosen to save himself despite the trouble it caused him to ultimately oversee the fate of a world he knew he eventually would become another memory in. Or Robo's pink plated girlfriend Atropos XR -- whose mainframe had been diluted by Mother Brain to loathe and even exterminate any human species in the Future. Despite being a robot, much like Robo was able to realize what her role meant in saving each timeline that would ultimately determine whether or not that humans were even able to exist in the world itself since she was a part of Mother Brain's regime. She sacrificed herself to in turn become the reason why Robo was able to not only reconcile his issues, but by doing so also put the gears of destiny for what was to become of Robo's resolve to shift into the gears of fate that ultimately led him to find the strength to continue on.....

Each character had such a deep storyline, although it was a storyline laced with debauchery, deep regrets, unavoidable lamented decisions, and writhe it was something that as a child despite how far over my head the deeper meaning of how it was written went that in a way I could still connect to what I understood initially of it. I could relate to the pain of not comprehending all of what was going on, and yet still pushing on ahead to see what would happen next in this world. As an adult, I was stricken by how relatable and how deep the character's storylines were. Because of how much this game also means to me because of the times I experienced while playing it. The music brings me back to an innocent, and later on an inherently aquired understanding of the world as I had known it in those times. 

As a child, I connected with the thirst of seeking adventure, the discovery of new unknown worlds, and incessant need to grind through the grit to ultimately feel accomplished in the feeling of having saved the world. As an adult, I connected with how deep each character's feelings became over time where they each initially were blinded by their own guilt, pain, despair, sorrow, and lack of wisdom through experiences that they were all ultimately able to reconcile their differences with. That, and how easy it was to understand why the protagonists felt the way they did about each of their struggles after facing many of my own as time passed on the road that I traveled to reach adulthood. That the struggles of fighting through the unknown to reach a precipice of peace, wisdom, and understanding was worth living with the tragedies, regrets, or the lament that we all in one way or another have experienced in our lives. It made me feel okay after replaying this game as an adult to feel exactly that way as an adult -- okay with living with myself, and accepting the price of being able to live with that comfortability of one's past or self  which is the amount of Sacrifice it takes each and every one of us in order to reach such a light of life to live in. They may be fictional characters but their stories each have a piece of a real person's heart in them. Those storylines didn't just come from imagination, they came from writers who were amazing enough to have shared those pieces of humanity with us through something as much as a SNES game. 

Personally, Squaresoft has always had a way of hitting heartstrings like this for me. Their writers must have experienced an incredible amount of existence in order to have conveyed such stories to us that from what I can tell has impacted the people like us who were lucky or blessed enough to have grinded through even the crappiest of parts who have been able to find a special feeling of Nostalgia that only games like these are able to provide. Each soundtrack now brings up individual memories in the times that I first heard them while making, or returned to for an almost childlike feeling of pureness for the comfort that by listening to them has and probably always will provide to me when I hear them. The more times I return to listen to them, the more nostalgia I end up creating for myself in the future the next time I hear them. Eventually, it becomes a soundtrack of our own....where the songs are ones we listen to when we feel a certain way, or are going through certain moments that remind us of them. That, or when we experience feelings that even the characters we came to love in those games went through. 

People can say they don't understand why these games or songs that are virtually unimportant to whomever coins such phrases when they approach us about why what seems so miniscule or unimportant to them like video game characters or music is something that is so important or life-changing to people like us......even if they may never understand the reasons why that is important to us, or how much it means to us I know deep down that as long as I'm able to feel that way I feel when revisiting those games or songs that honestly is a good portion of why I was able to grow into the person I've become, and that without such memories or feelings because of how much those things influenced me that I wouldn't be the person they -- or even myself knew without them.

*CHECKPOINT* This literally made my heart get back on track and in the rythym of beating correctly because of how much love, and meaning these comments have in them, and because of how much this game really does mean to me. One of many, a fraction of what each game like this one means to me or the reasons why my purpose, and level of diversity and emotional depth are structured the way they are inside of my heart. Some video games are simply that -- just a game. Chrono Trigger is a forever changing motion in my heart though. I don't think I would be as aware or as understanding as I am if it weren't for storylines and soundtracks like these. Thank you Squaresoft, for everything that you shared with us. Enix doesn't have that magical 90's charm that Square does. These were the times that dialogues in games or really anything like that were scripts that were groundbreaking and were able to reach an audience of society that I don't believe would have been tapped into the way it was without them existing in formats such as this. I can't imagine a life without experiences or the feelings of nostalgia like the ones games like Chrono Trigger are able to create. It's so magical to me to see how much games like this also mean to other people in the comments. It makes me happy to know that even if time attempts to bury games or songs like this that ultimately there will be people like us who will be there to unearth them, and will always be around to show our appreciation for them. How is any generation ahead of this one supposed to expand in a virtually nostalgic and important way without having the joy we were able to have while experiencing games like this before being poisoned by new gen systems, and storylines in games that don't have the kind of heart that our generation of gaming had in them? Again it's games and songs like these that allowed my structure as a human to expand and grow as widely as it has. It makes me sad to know that to a degree there will be that barrier to blockade the magic these games hold inside of them because of something like the graphics not being 3D/bad looking, or the music not being electronica or dubstepped out in the background, or the lack of selection, and the amount of cryptic and almost impossible to guess on your own how to find or complete tasks or quests in games like this. That to me is what made these games also so worthwhile was the feeling of finding that one item or one NPC with a secret storyline was.
